  "prompt": "What are the main differences between the engines in jet fighters and the engines in airliners?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between jet engines in fighters and airliners:\n\nFighter Jet Engines:\n1. Designed for high thrust-to-weight ratio\n2. Optimized for high speed and maneuverability\n3. Often use afterburners for temporary extreme thrust\n4. Shorter operational lifespan\n5. More complex and expensive\n6. Can operate at very high altitudes and extreme angles\n7. Primarily use turbofan or turbojet designs\n\nAirliner Engines:\n1. Focused on fuel efficiency and reliability\n2. Designed for sustained, steady performance\n3. No afterburners\n4. Longer operational lifespan\n5. More cost-effective to manufacture and maintain\n6. Optimized for cruising at consistent altitudes\n7. Primarily use high-bypass turbofan designs\n8. Larger fan diameter for better fuel economy\n9. Lower maximum speed capabilities\n\nThe primary goal for fighter engines is performance and combat capability, while airliner engines prioritize efficiency, range, and consistent operation.",
